<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="427" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[816,1429,1281,2019]" box="[816,919,1281,1307]" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis box="[816,919,1281,1307]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[816,1429,1281,2019]" lastBlockId="15.[159,771,223,418]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="427" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">
This small species can be distinguished from most 
<taxonomicName box="[885,1042,1349,1375]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[885,1042,1349,1375]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">Hipposideros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by smaller body size (
<tableCitation box="[1326,1420,1349,1375]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="10.[99,112,501,522]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="TABLE 2. Measurements of nine external traits of 52 bat species. FA — forearm length, BM — body mass, HB — head and body length, TL — tail length, TB — tibia length, HF — hind foot length, TU — thumb length: EL — ear length, TR — tragus length. Numbers denote minimum and maximum, and sample size; values in parentheses indicate measurements of specimens of this study; ‘ – ’: data not available. BMs for specimens were taken in the field. All measurements in mm, except for BM (in g)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/1DCD6623FFA8BF319968FE17FA147437" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" tableUuid="1DCD6623FFA8BF319968FE17FA147437">Table 2</tableCitation>
) and from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1871" box="[934,1048,1383,1409]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="doriae">
<emphasis box="[934,1048,1383,1409]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">H. doriae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by presence of vertical septa in the posterior noseleaf. In comparison with species of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[864,949,1450,1476]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[864,949,1450,1476]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group known for the Sunda Shelf, the body size and noseleaf shape were closest to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Templeton" authorityYear="1848" box="[849,932,1518,1544]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis box="[849,932,1518,1544]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">H. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blyth" authorityYear="1853" box="[948,1111,1518,1544]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cineraceus">
<emphasis box="[948,1111,1518,1544]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">H. cineraceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1902" box="[1177,1331,1518,1544]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dyacorum">
<emphasis box="[1177,1331,1518,1544]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">H. dyacorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Corbet and Hill" firstAuthor="Corbet" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" refId="ref25099" refString="CORBET, G. B., and J. E. HILL. 1992. The mammals of the Indomalayan Region: a systematic review. Natural History Museum Publications, Oxford, 488 pp." type="book" year="1992">Corbet and Hill, 1992</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasuma" box="[1001,1239,1552,1578]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Yasuma" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" refId="ref29128" refString="YASUMA, S., M. AADAU, L. APIN, F. T. Y. YA, and L. KIMSUI. 2003. Identification Keys to the Mammals of Borneo. Sabah Parks and JICA, Kota Kinabalu, 85 pp." type="book" year="2003">
Yasuma 
<emphasis box="[1102,1162,1552,1578]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">et al.</emphasis>
, 2003
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Francis" box="[1251,1413,1552,1578]" firstAuthor="Francis" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" refId="ref25558" refString="FRANCIS, C. M. 2008. A guide to mammals of Southeast Asia. Princeton University Press, Princeton, NJ, 392 pp." type="book" year="2008">Francis, 2008</bibRefCitation>
). The internarial septum is pinkish or grayish purple, and the top half of the ear is rounded, contrasting with the darkish septum and triangular ears of 
<emphasis box="[816,981,1688,1714]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1902" box="[816,977,1688,1714]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dyacorum">H. dyacorum</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The internarial septum is swollen at the base and gradually narrows towards the top, a condition similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Templeton" authorityYear="1848" box="[1083,1168,1755,1781]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis box="[1083,1168,1755,1781]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">H. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[1245,1395,1755,1781]" country="Malaysia" name="Pahang" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">Pahang state</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[816,924,1789,1815]" name="Malaysia" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
and different from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blyth" authorityYear="1853" box="[1185,1356,1789,1815]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cineraceus">
<emphasis box="[1185,1356,1789,1815]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">H. cineraceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[816,905,1823,1849]" country="Malaysia" name="Pahang" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">Pahang</collectingRegion>
, in which the internarial septum is swollen at the middle (
<bibRefCitation author="Kingston" box="[957,1209,1857,1883]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Kingston" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" refId="ref26934" refString="KINGSTON, T., B. L. LIM, and A. ZUBAID. 2006. Bats of Krau Wildlife Reserve. Penerbit Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, Bangi, 145 pp." type="book" year="2006">
Kingston 
<emphasis box="[1074,1134,1857,1883]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">et al.</emphasis>
, 2006
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1902" box="[1275,1428,1857,1883]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dyacorum">
<emphasis box="[1275,1428,1857,1883]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">H. dyacorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[882,990,1891,1917]" name="Malaysia" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
which is very narrow (
<bibRefCitation author="Murray" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Murray" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" pagination="597 - 661" refId="ref27457" refString="MURRAY, S. W., P. CAMPBELL, T. KINGSTON, A. ZUBAID, C. M. FRANCIS, and T. H. KUNZ. 2012. Molecular phylogeny of hipposiderid bats from Southeast Asia and evidence of cryptic diversity. Molecular Phylogentics and Evolution, 62: 597 - 661." type="journal article" year="2012">
Murray 
<emphasis box="[1362,1421,1891,1917]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="426">et al.</emphasis>
, 2012
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="KHAN, F. A. A." box="[905,1078,1925,1951]" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" refId="ref26525" refString="KHAN, F. A. A. 2013. Diversification of Old World bats in Southeast Asia: speciation and phylogeographic studies. PhD. Dissertation, Texas Tech University, Lubbock, ix + 257 pp." type="book" year="2013">Khan’s (2013)</bibRefCitation>
molecular analysis included one sample from Way Canguk Forest and found it to be genetically identical to the Java population of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Templeton" authorityYear="1848" box="[159,247,223,249]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis box="[159,247,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">H. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<emphasis box="[307,461,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">H. a. saevus</emphasis>
-1 by the author). In our study area, it is smaller than 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[525,651,257,283]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[525,651,257,283]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">H. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see species account below) but bigger than 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1871" box="[597,712,291,317]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="doriae">
<emphasis box="[597,712,291,317]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">H. doriae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gould" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[487,626,325,351]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cervinus">
<emphasis box="[487,626,325,351]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">H. cervinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by absence of lateral leaflets on the muzzle and smaller body size.
</paragraph>
